Class Terminal

  • Object
    • Terminal
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    EmergencyState, Encodable, OccupancyLevel
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AirplaneTerminal, HelicopterTerminal
    public abstract class Terminal
extends Object
implements EmergencyState, OccupancyLevel, Encodable
    Represents an airport terminal building, containing several aircraft gates.
    Partially implemented in assignment 1, to be completed in assignment 2

    • Constructor Detail

      • Terminal

        protected Terminal​(int terminalNumber)
        Creates a new Terminal with the given unique terminal number.

        It is not the responsibility of the Terminal class to ensure terminal numbers are unique. Instead, the user should check that no other terminal of the same type exists with the same terminal number when instantiating a new terminal.

        Newly created terminals should not be in a state of emergency by default.

        Parameters:
        terminalNumber - identifying number of this terminal
        Implemented in assignment 1

      • addGate

        public void addGate​(Gate gate)
             throws NoSpaceException
        Adds a gate to the terminal.

        If the terminal is currently at maximum capacity (MAX_NUM_GATES), then the gate should not be added, and instead a NoSpaceException should be thrown.

        Parameters:
        gate - gate to add to terminal
        Throws:
        NoSpaceException - if there is no space at the terminal for the new gate
        Implemented in assignment 1

      • getGates

        public List<Gate> getGates()
        Returns a list of all gates in the terminal.

        The order in which gates appear in this list should be the same as the order in which they were added by calling addGate(Gate).

        Adding or removing elements from the returned list should not affect the original list.

        Returns:
        list of terminal's gates
        Implemented in assignment 1

      • findUnoccupiedGate

        public Gate findUnoccupiedGate()
                        throws NoSuitableGateException
        Finds and returns the first non-occupied gate in this terminal.

        Gates should be searched in the same order as in getGates().

        If all gates in this terminal are occupied with an aircraft, throws a NoSuitableGateException.

        Returns:
        first non-occupied gate in this terminal
        Throws:
        NoSuitableGateException - if all gates in this terminal are occupied

      • calculateOccupancyLevel

        public int calculateOccupancyLevel()
        Returns the ratio of occupied gates to total gates as a percentage from 0 to 100.

        If there are no gates in this terminal, 0 should be returned. The ratio should be rounded to the nearest whole percentage.

        For example, if the terminal has 3 gates and 2 are occupied, the ratio should be 2/3 = 0.666... and the rounded percentage is 67%, so 67 should be returned.

        Specified by:
        calculateOccupancyLevel in interface OccupancyLevel
        Returns:
        percentage of occupied gates in this terminal, 0 to 100
        Implemented in assignment 1

      • toString

        public String toString()
        Returns the human-readable string representation of this terminal.

        The format of the string to return is 

        TerminalType terminalNum, numGates gates
        where TerminalType is the class name of the concrete terminal class (i.e. AirplaneTerminal or HelicopterTerminal), terminalNum is the terminal number and numGates is the number of gates in the terminal. If the terminal is currently in a state of emergency, the format of the string to return is 
        TerminalType terminalNum, numGates gates (EMERGENCY)
        For example, "Terminal 3, 5 gates (EMERGENCY)".

        Hint: Object#getClass().getSimpleName() can be used to find the class name of an object.

        Overrides:
        toString in class Object
        Returns:
        string representation of this terminal
        Implemented in assignment 1

      • encode

        public String encode()
        Returns the machine-readable string representation of this terminal.

        The format of the string to return is 

        TerminalType:terminalNumber:emergency:numGates
encodedGate1
encodedGate2
...
encodedGateN
        where
        • TerminalType is the simple class name of this terminal, e.g. AirplaneTerminal
        • terminalNumber is the terminal number of this terminal
        • emergency is whether or not this terminal is in a state of emergency
        • numGates is the number of gates in this terminal
        • encodedGateX is the encoded representation of the Xth gate in this terminal, for X between 1 and N inclusive, where N is the number of gates, in the same order as returned by getGates()
        For example: 
        HelicopterTerminal:3:false:0
        For example: 
        AirplaneTerminal:1:true:3
1:empty
2:ABC123
3:empty
        Specified by:
        encode in interface Encodable
        Returns:
        encoded string representation of this terminal
        Implement this for assignment 2
